    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 47,
      "content": "a. Excretion"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 48,
      "content": "Solifenacin Succinate is eliminated from the body through both renal and fecal routes. Approximately 70% of the"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 49,
      "content": "administered dose is recovered in the urine, primarily as metabolites, and about 23% is recovered in the feces. The"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 50,
      "content": "terminal elimination half-life is approximately 5-8 hours."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 51,
      "content": "b. Physicochemical Properties"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 52,
      "content": "Solifenacin Succinate is a white to off-white crystalline powder. It is sparingly soluble in water and methanol, and"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 53,
      "content": "slightly soluble in ethanol. The pH of a 1% aqueous solution is typically between 4.0 and 5.5. The melting point is"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 54,
      "content": "approximately 130-135 °C. It exhibits polymorphism, with different crystalline forms potentially affecting its"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 55,
      "content": "dissolution and bioavailability."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 56,
      "content": "c. Preformulation Study and Selection of Excipients"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 57,
      "content": "Preformulation studies were conducted to understand the physicochemical properties of Solifenacin Succinate and to"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 58,
      "content": "identify suitable excipients for the development of a stable and effective oral dosage form. These studies included"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 59,
      "content": "characterization of solubility, stability, particle size, and compatibility with potential excipients. The goal was to select"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 60,
      "content": "excipients that would ensure adequate drug release, tablet integrity, and long-term stability."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 61,
      "content": "Preformulation Study Stages"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 62,
      "content": "The preformulation study involved several stages: 1. Characterization of the Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient (API):"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 63,
      "content": "This included determining its physical form, solubility profile across a range of pH values, melting point, and"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 64,
      "content": "hygroscopicity. 2. Excipient Screening: A range of common pharmaceutical excipients were screened for"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 65,
      "content": "compatibility with Solifenacin Succinate using techniques such as Differential Scanning Calorimetry (DSC) and"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 66,
      "content": "Fourier Transform Infrared Spectroscopy (FTIR). 3. Processability Assessment: Preliminary studies were performed"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 67,
      "content": "to evaluate the API's flow properties and compressibility, essential for tablet manufacturing. 4. Stability Studies: The"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 68,
      "content": "intrinsic stability of Solifenacin Succinate under various stress conditions (heat, humidity, light) was assessed to guide"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
      "sn": 69,
      "content": "formulation and storage recommendations."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 4,
