      "content": "Product Name: Solifenacin Succinate Tablets BP 5 mg Film coated tablets 5 mg"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 105,
      "content": "e. Excipients Information and Compatibility"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 106,
      "content": "The selected excipients for Solifenacin Succinate Tablets 5 mg are Lactose Monohydrate (diluent), Maize starch"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 107,
      "content": "(diluent/binder), Hypromellose (binder), Magnesium Stearate (lubricant), and Readycoat Iron Oxide Yellow (film"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 108,
      "content": "former). Compatibility studies, including DSC and FTIR, were performed to ensure no adverse interactions between"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 109,
      "content": "Solifenacin Succinate and these excipients. The results indicated good compatibility, with no significant degradation"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 110,
      "content": "or formation of new impurities observed under accelerated storage conditions. The chosen excipients are"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 111,
      "content": "pharmacopoeially approved and suitable for direct compression or wet granulation processes, facilitating robust tablet"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 112,
      "content": "manufacturing."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 113,
      "content": "f. Excipient Selection Rationale"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 114,
      "content": "Lactose Monohydrate was selected as the primary diluent due to its excellent compressibility and inertness, providing"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 115,
      "content": "bulk to the tablet. Maize starch serves a dual role as a diluent and binder, enhancing tablet hardness and aiding"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 116,
      "content": "disintegration. Hypromellose was chosen as a binder to ensure adequate granule strength and tablet cohesion."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 117,
      "content": "Magnesium Stearate was incorporated as a lubricant to prevent sticking to the tablet tooling during compression. The"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 118,
      "content": "film coating system, Readycoat Iron Oxide Yellow, was selected for its film-forming properties, providing a uniform"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 119,
      "content": "coating, enhancing tablet appearance with a distinct color for identification, and offering protection to the tablet core."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 120,
      "content": "All excipients are of pharmacopoeial grade and have a well-established history of use in oral solid dosage forms."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "section_title": null,
      "page": 5,
      "sn": 121,
